~ tutorial
Shopkeeper: First things first. I'll neeed to explain how the Cullings really work. 
Shopkeeper: Besides infecting people with spots of corruption that quite literally suck the life out of them, the Cullings also yield a residual substance that attaches itself to worldly, man-made items. 
Shopkeeper: While the manner in which said corruption targets and attaches itself to people or items is seemingly random, there's surely a logic and a purpose to it, known only to the Goddess Herself.
Shopkeeper: Whenever the sky turns red in the morning - a harbinger of the Cullings, as you well know - some people die, and some items become corrupted. 
Shopkeeper: While the goodwill of our Goddess has fortunately kept us safe from the former, we have sadly not been unaffected by the latter. 
Shopkeeper: Interesting thing is, the residual substance that attaches itself to objects is invisible to the human eye. 
Shopkeeper: Anyone can see the spots of corruption that cause people to die gruesome deaths. But only a few of us, who have had the good fortune of being blessed by the Goddess with Her Gift of sight, can see the spots of corruption that infect our everyday objects. 
Shopkeeper: Though most people can't see said spots, their side effects can be felt by anyone. Using, interacting with or looking at an infected object can cause madness, ilness, and the appearance of violent urges.
Shopkeeper: Sometimes, people can even hear the object talking to them, inciting them to violence. No wonder they go mad. 
Shopkeeper: Luckily, you and I can rid the items of their evil. And that's why people send them to us. 
Shopkeeper: All we gotta do is, quite literally, rip the evil spots off like a bandaid using our little hands and fingers. 
#tutorial start
Shopkeeper: [do lock_player_action("complete_object", true)][do lock_player_action("complete_sticker", true)][do lock_player_action("focus_object", true)]There. Look down and to your left. There's an infected object on the table. Pick it up and put it down in front of you, for now. [do DialogueFuncs.add_object_to_workbench("tutorial_peel_book")] [do wait_for("first_drag_on_object")]   
#tutorial: look down, move objects, quarantine zone
Shopkeeper: Now pick it up again and give it a proper look. Rotate it around, try to really focus on it. Make sure to put it back down after a few seconds. [do lock_player_action("focus_object", false)] [do wait_for("first_rotate_on_object")] 
#tutorial: focus mode, rotate 
Shopkeeper: Feels weird, eh? Focus on it long enough and you might just die. No, really, I'm not kidding.
Shopkeeper: You need constant breaks in our line of work. Whenever it starts to hurt, or when you feel like you might be losing it, put the item down. Take a moment to breathe.
Shopkeeper: You'll feel fine again soon enough. And then you're back to peeling. 
Shopkeeper: Speaking of, let's try peeling the evil off this one. 
Shopkeeper: Pick it back up, focus on it, and run your fingers over those weird looking spots. Then peel. Remember, take breaks if you feel the need. [do lock_player_action("complete_sticker", false)] [do wait_for("first_sticker_cleansed_on_object")] 
#tutorial: managing your health, peeling 
Shopkeeper: Well done. Now get rid of all corruption spots and when you're done put it in the basket, to your right. [do lock_player_action("complete_object", false)] [do wait_for("object_completed")] => normal_spots_complete_check
#tutorial: done zone

# TODO DANI: Do a pass over repetitive sections to vary responses. Only replace text! Keep "do" instructions in the same order!
#tutorial: Repeating normal spots object based on player performance 
~ normal_spots_complete_check
if Variables.get_var("prog_score_special_object_tutorial_peel_book") < 100
	% Shopkeeper: No worries, no one gets it right the first time. Try again.
	% Shopkeeper: Almost. You've got it this time. Give it another try. 
	
	% Shopkeeper: You have to get rid of all corruption spots and when you're done put it in the basket, to your right. [do DialogueFuncs.add_object_to_workbench("tutorial_peel_book")] [do wait_for("object_completed")] => normal_spots_complete_check
	% Shopkeeper: Fully cleanse the object and and then put it in the basket, to your right. [do DialogueFuncs.add_object_to_workbench("tutorial_peel_book")] [do wait_for("object_completed")] => normal_spots_complete_check
else 
	Shopkeeper: It's clean, well done! Now let's try another one. 
	Shopkeeper: But remember, put down the objects from time to time. Better it stay as it is than you become infected yourself. Items can be burned, but you can't come back if the evil gets its hooks in you. 
	Shopkeeper: This next one has been infected longer. Its evil is more frenetic. Some of its spots will move inward when observed for too long, infecting it forever. Give it a go. [do DialogueFuncs.add_object_to_workbench("tutorial_timed_milk_carton")] [do wait_for("object_completed")] => timed_spots_complete_check
	
#tutorial: Repeating timed spots object based on player performance
~ timed_spots_complete_check
if Variables.get_var("prog_score_special_object_tutorial_timed_milk_carton") < 100
	% Shopkeeper: Yep, this one's trickier. Give it another go.
	% Shopkeeper: Still better than I was at first. No harm done. Again.
	
	% Shopkeeper: You have to get rid of all corruption spots and when you're done put it in the basket, to your right. [do DialogueFuncs.add_object_to_workbench("tutorial_timed_milk_carton")] [do wait_for("object_completed")]  => timed_spots_complete_check
	% Shopkeeper: Fully cleanse the object and and then put it in the basket, to your right. [do DialogueFuncs.add_object_to_workbench("tutorial_timed_milk_carton")] [do wait_for("object_completed")]  => timed_spots_complete_check
else 
	Shopkeeper: Great job. You're a natural, eh? One last object I want to show you. 
	Shopkeeper: This one has directional spots. Try to cleanse it. [do DialogueFuncs.add_object_to_workbench("tutorial_directional_chess_set")] [do wait_for("object_completed")] => directional_spots_complete_check
# TODO DANI: Add directional spots description

#tutorial: Repeating directional spots object based on player performance
~ directional_spots_complete_check
if Variables.get_var("prog_score_special_object_tutorial_directional_chess_set") < 100
	% Shopkeeper: Yep, this one's trickier. Give it another go.
	% Shopkeeper: Still better than I was at first. No harm done. Again.
	
	% Shopkeeper: You have to get rid of all corruption spots and when you're done put it in the basket, to your right. [do DialogueFuncs.add_object_to_workbench("tutorial_directional_chess_set")] [do wait_for("object_completed")] => directional_spots_complete_check
	% Shopkeeper: Fully cleanse the object and and then put it in the basket, to your right. [do DialogueFuncs.add_object_to_workbench("tutorial_directional_chess_set")] [do wait_for("object_completed")] => directional_spots_complete_check
else 
	Shopkeeper: There we go. In the basket it goes => spots_tutorial_end

~ spots_tutorial_end
Shopkeeper: That's it. Our day consists of doing this over and over again, taking short breaks whenever we feel the need, and longer ones once every two or three objects. Safer that way. Easy to get lost in this kind of work. 
Shopkeeper: Like I said, make sure you don't get too absorbed in it. Look around, talk to me or to whoever finds themselves in this sorry place, peer out the window, anything. Balance is key. 
Shopkeeper: You can keep practicing, if you so wish. These items are from old batches, anyway. Their owners are long dead. Mostly.
